      "answer": 0,
      "explanation": "The displacement is $\\mathbf{d} = \\overrightarrow{PQ} = (5-2)\\mathbf{i} + (-1-1)\\mathbf{j} + (4-1)\\mathbf{k} = 3\\mathbf{i} - 2\\mathbf{j} + 3\\mathbf{k}$. Then $W = \\mathbf{F} \\cdot \\mathbf{d} = (2)(3) + (-1)(-2) + (4)(3) = 6 + 2 + 12 = 20$ joules. The option $27$ dots $\\mathbf{F}$ with the position vector of $Q$ instead of the displacement, $16$ mishandles the double negative in $(-1)(-2)$, and $-20$ computes $\\overrightarrow{QP}$ as if the particle moved the other way. The trap is using a position vector where the work formula demands the displacement, the difference of the two positions.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 12"
