    {
      "id": "vectors-and-mechanics-products-of-vectors-022",
      "stem": "Find the area of the parallelogram with adjacent sides $\\mathbf{a} = \\mathbf{i} + 2\\mathbf{j} + 2\\mathbf{k}$ and $\\mathbf{b} = 2\\mathbf{i} + \\mathbf{k}$.",
      "options": [
        "$\\frac{\\sqrt{29}}{2}$",
        "$4$",
        "$\\sqrt{29}$",
        "$3\\sqrt{5}$"
      ],
      "answer": 2,
      "explanation": "The area of a parallelogram with adjacent sides $\\mathbf{a}$ and $\\mathbf{b}$ is $|\\mathbf{a} \\times \\mathbf{b}|$. The cross product has $\\mathbf{i}$ component $(2)(1) - (2)(0) = 2$, $\\mathbf{j}$ component $-\\left[(1)(1) - (2)(2)\\right] = 3$, and $\\mathbf{k}$ component $(1)(0) - (2)(2) = -4$, so $\\mathbf{a} \\times \\mathbf{b} = 2\\mathbf{i} + 3\\mathbf{j} - 4\\mathbf{k}$ and the area is $\\sqrt{4 + 9 + 16} = \\sqrt{29}$. The option $\\frac{\\sqrt{29}}{2}$ halves as though the figure were a triangle, $4$ is the dot product $\\mathbf{a} \\cdot \\mathbf{b}$ pressed into service, and $3\\sqrt{5}$ multiplies the side lengths $|\\mathbf{a}| = 3$ and $|\\mathbf{b}| = \\sqrt{5}$, which only works for a rectangle. The trap is reaching for the dot product when area questions belong to the cross product.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 12"
    },
    {
      "id": "vectors-and-mechanics-products-of-vectors-023",
      "stem": "Find the area of the triangle with vertices $P(1, 0, 0)$, $Q(0, 2, 0)$, and $R(0, 0, 3)$.",
      "options": [
        "$7$",
        "$\\frac{49}{2}$",
        "$\\frac{5\\sqrt{2}}{2}$",
