      ],
      "answer": 3,
      "explanation": "Form two edge vectors from the same vertex: $\\overrightarrow{PQ} = -\\mathbf{i} + 2\\mathbf{j}$ and $\\overrightarrow{PR} = -\\mathbf{i} + 3\\mathbf{k}$. Their cross product has $\\mathbf{i}$ component $(2)(3) - (0)(0) = 6$, $\\mathbf{j}$ component $-\\left[(-1)(3) - (0)(-1)\\right] = 3$, and $\\mathbf{k}$ component $(-1)(0) - (2)(-1) = 2$, so the cross product is $6\\mathbf{i} + 3\\mathbf{j} + 2\\mathbf{k}$ with magnitude $\\sqrt{36 + 9 + 4} = 7$. The triangle is half the parallelogram, so its area is $\\frac{7}{2}$. The option $7$ forgets the half, $\\frac{49}{2}$ forgets the square root, and $\\frac{5\\sqrt{2}}{2}$ multiplies $\\frac{1}{2}|\\overrightarrow{PQ}||\\overrightarrow{PR}|$ as though the angle at $P$ were a right angle. The trap is the missing factor of one half that separates the triangle from the parallelogram.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 12"
    },
    {
      "id": "vectors-and-mechanics-products-of-vectors-024",
      "stem": "The diagonals of a parallelogram are $\\mathbf{d}_1 = 3\\mathbf{i} + \\mathbf{j} - 2\\mathbf{k}$ and $\\mathbf{d}_2 = \\mathbf{i} - 3\\mathbf{j} + 4\\mathbf{k}$. Find the area of the parallelogram.",
