      "explanation": "When the diagonals are given, the area is $\\frac{1}{2}|\\mathbf{d}_1 \\times \\mathbf{d}_2|$, since writing the sides as $\\mathbf{a}$ and $\\mathbf{b}$ gives $\\mathbf{d}_1 = \\mathbf{a} + \\mathbf{b}$, $\\mathbf{d}_2 = \\mathbf{b} - \\mathbf{a}$, and $\\mathbf{d}_1 \\times \\mathbf{d}_2 = 2(\\mathbf{a} \\times \\mathbf{b})$. The cross product has $\\mathbf{i}$ component $(1)(4) - (-2)(-3) = -2$, $\\mathbf{j}$ component $-\\left[(3)(4) - (-2)(1)\\right] = -14$, and $\\mathbf{k}$ component $(3)(-3) - (1)(1) = -10$, with magnitude $\\sqrt{4 + 196 + 100} = \\sqrt{300} = 10\\sqrt{3}$. Half of that is $5\\sqrt{3}$. The option $10\\sqrt{3}$ treats the diagonals as if they were sides and skips the half, $\\frac{5\\sqrt{3}}{2}$ halves a second time, and $4$ reaches for $\\frac{1}{2}|\\mathbf{d}_1 \\cdot \\mathbf{d}_2|$ with the wrong product. The trap is forgetting the factor of one half that converts the diagonal cross product into the area.",
      "difficulty": "stretch",
      "source": "in the style of Weatherburn, Elementary Vector Analysis"
