    {
      "id": "vectors-and-mechanics-products-of-vectors-025",
      "stem": "Let $\\mathbf{a} = \\mathbf{i} + 2\\mathbf{j} - \\mathbf{k}$, $\\mathbf{b} = 3\\mathbf{i} + 2\\mathbf{k}$, and $\\mathbf{c} = \\mathbf{i} + \\mathbf{j} + \\mathbf{k}$. Compute the scalar triple product $\\mathbf{a} \\cdot (\\mathbf{b} \\times \\mathbf{c})$.",
      "options": [
        "$-3$",
        "$-7$",
        "$7$",
        "$-1$"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "The scalar triple product is the determinant with rows $1, 2, -1$, then $3, 0, 2$, then $1, 1, 1$. Expanding along the first row: $1\\left[(0)(1) - (2)(1)\\right] - 2\\left[(3)(1) - (2)(1)\\right] + (-1)\\left[(3)(1) - (0)(1)\\right] = -2 - 2 - 3 = -7$. Computing $\\mathbf{b} \\times \\mathbf{c} = -2\\mathbf{i} - \\mathbf{j} + 3\\mathbf{k}$ first and then dotting with $\\mathbf{a}$ gives the same $-2 - 2 - 3 = -7$. The option $-3$ forgets to negate the middle cofactor, $-1$ flips the sign of the last term, and $7$ discards the overall sign even though nothing here asks for a volume. The trap is the middle term of the cofactor expansion, which must be subtracted, not added.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 12"
    },
    {
      "id": "vectors-and-mechanics-products-of-vectors-026",
      "stem": "A parallelepiped has coterminous edges $\\mathbf{a} = \\mathbf{i} + \\mathbf{j}$, $\\mathbf{b} = \\mathbf{i} + \\mathbf{k}$, and $\\mathbf{c} = \\mathbf{j} + \\mathbf{k}$. Find its volume.",
      "options": [
        "$2$",
        "$-2$",
        "$0$",
        "$2\\sqrt{2}$"
      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explanation": "The volume is the absolute value of the scalar triple product, $V = |\\mathbf{a} \\cdot (\\mathbf{b} \\times \\mathbf{c})|$. The determinant with rows $1, 1, 0$, then $1, 0, 1$, then $0, 1, 1$ expands to $1\\left[(0)(1) - (1)(1)\\right] - 1\\left[(1)(1) - (1)(0)\\right] + 0 = -1 - 1 = -2$, so the volume is $|-2| = 2$. The option $-2$ reports the raw triple product, but a volume cannot be negative; the sign only records orientation. The option $0$ comes from failing to negate the middle cofactor, which collapses $-1 - 1$ into $-1 + 1$ and falsely suggests the edges are coplanar, while $2\\sqrt{2}$ multiplies the three edge lengths as if the box were rectangular. The trap is forgetting the absolute value when converting a signed triple product into a volume.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 12"
    },
    {
      "id": "vectors-and-mechanics-products-of-vectors-027",
      "stem": "Find the value of $\\lambda$ for which the vectors $\\mathbf{a} = \\mathbf{i} + 2\\mathbf{j} + 3\\mathbf{k}$, $\\mathbf{b} = 2\\mathbf{i} - \\mathbf{j} + \\mathbf{k}$, and $\\mathbf{c} = \\lambda\\mathbf{i} + \\mathbf{j} + 4\\mathbf{k}$ are coplanar.",
      "options": [
        "$\\lambda = -3$",
        "$\\lambda = 3$",
        "$\\lambda = -17$",
        "$\\lambda = 15$"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "Three vectors are coplanar exactly when their scalar triple product vanishes. The determinant with rows $1, 2, 3$, then $2, -1, 1$, then $\\lambda, 1, 4$ expands along the first row to $1(-4 - 1) - 2(8 - \\lambda) + 3(2 + \\lambda) = -5 - 16 + 2\\lambda + 6 + 3\\lambda = 5\\lambda - 15$. Setting $5\\lambda - 15 = 0$ gives $\\lambda = 3$, and indeed with $\\lambda = 3$ one checks $\\mathbf{c} = \\mathbf{a} + \\mathbf{b}$, which confirms coplanarity directly. The option $\\lambda = -3$ solves $5\\lambda + 15 = 0$ after a sign slip, $\\lambda = -17$ comes from failing to negate the middle cofactor, which yields $17 + \\lambda = 0$, and $\\lambda = 15$ forgets to divide by the coefficient $5$. The trap is the subtracted middle term in the determinant expansion, the most common source of a wrong coplanarity condition.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 12"
    },
    {
      "id": "vectors-and-mechanics-products-of-vectors-028",
      "stem": "Determine whether the vectors $\\mathbf{a} = \\mathbf{i} - \\mathbf{j} + 2\\mathbf{k}$, $\\mathbf{b} = 2\\mathbf{i} + \\mathbf{j} - \\mathbf{k}$, and $\\mathbf{c} = 3\\mathbf{i} + \\mathbf{k}$ are coplanar.",
      "options": [
        "They are not coplanar, because $\\mathbf{a} \\cdot (\\mathbf{b} \\times \\mathbf{c}) = -10$",
        "They are not coplanar, because $\\mathbf{a} \\cdot (\\mathbf{b} \\times \\mathbf{c}) = 12$",
        "They are not coplanar, because no two of the vectors are parallel",
        "They are coplanar, because $\\mathbf{a} \\cdot (\\mathbf{b} \\times \\mathbf{c}) = 0$"
      ],
      "answer": 3,
      "explanation": "Compute the scalar triple product as the determinant with rows $1, -1, 2$, then $2, 1, -1$, then $3, 0, 1$. Expanding along the first row: $1\\left[(1)(1) - (-1)(0)\\right] + 1\\left[(2)(1) - (-1)(3)\\right] + 2\\left[(2)(0) - (1)(3)\\right] = 1 + 5 - 6 = 0$, so the three vectors are coplanar. In fact $\\mathbf{c} = \\mathbf{a} + \\mathbf{b}$, so $\\mathbf{c}$ lies in the plane spanned by the other two. The value $-10$ comes from failing to negate the middle cofactor, $12$ from a sign slip in the last term, and the third option wrongly believes coplanarity requires some pair to be parallel, when linear dependence is the real criterion. The trap is judging coplanarity by eye instead of testing whether the scalar triple product is zero.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 12"
    },
    {
      "id": "vectors-and-mechanics-products-of-vectors-029",
      "stem": "A tetrahedron has coterminous edges $\\mathbf{a} = \\mathbf{i} + 2\\mathbf{j}$, $\\mathbf{b} = \\mathbf{j} + 3\\mathbf{k}$, and $\\mathbf{c} = 2\\mathbf{i} + \\mathbf{j} + \\mathbf{k}$. Find its volume.",
      "options": [
        "$\\frac{10}{3}$",
        "$10$",
        "$\\frac{5}{3}$",
        "$5$"
      ],
      "answer": 2,
      "explanation": "The scalar triple product is the determinant with rows $1, 2, 0$, then $0, 1, 3$, then $2, 1, 1$: expanding along the first row gives $1\\left[(1)(1) - (3)(1)\\right] - 2\\left[(0)(1) - (3)(2)\\right] + 0 = -2 + 12 = 10$. That is the volume of the parallelepiped on the three edges; the tetrahedron on the same edges occupies one sixth of it, so $V = \\frac{1}{6}|10| = \\frac{5}{3}$. The factor $\\frac{1}{6}$ comes from the half that turns the base parallelogram into a triangle and the third in the cone-volume rule $\\frac{1}{3} \\times \\text{base} \\times \\text{height}$. The option $10$ stops at the parallelepiped, $5$ applies only the half, and $\\frac{10}{3}$ applies only the third. The trap is forgetting that a tetrahedron needs the full factor of one sixth, not just one of its two pieces.",
      "difficulty": "stretch",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 12"
    },
    {
      "id": "vectors-and-mechanics-products-of-vectors-030",
      "stem": "Let $\\mathbf{a}$, $\\mathbf{b}$, $\\mathbf{c}$ be nonzero vectors, no two of which are parallel. Which condition guarantees that the three vectors are coplanar?",
      "options": [
        "$\\mathbf{a} \\times (\\mathbf{b} \\times \\mathbf{c}) = \\mathbf{0}$",
        "$\\mathbf{a} \\cdot (\\mathbf{b} \\times \\mathbf{c}) = 0$",
        "$\\mathbf{a} \\cdot \\mathbf{b} = \\mathbf{b} \\cdot \\mathbf{c} = \\mathbf{c} \\cdot \\mathbf{a} = 0$",
        "$\\left|\\mathbf{a} \\cdot (\\mathbf{b} \\times \\mathbf{c})\\right| = 1$"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "The vector $\\mathbf{b} \\times \\mathbf{c}$ is normal to the plane spanned by $\\mathbf{b}$ and $\\mathbf{c}$, so $\\mathbf{a} \\cdot (\\mathbf{b} \\times \\mathbf{c}) = 0$ says precisely that $\\mathbf{a}$ lies in that plane; equivalently, the parallelepiped on the three vectors has zero volume. The vector triple product condition $\\mathbf{a} \\times (\\mathbf{b} \\times \\mathbf{c}) = \\mathbf{0}$ says instead that $\\mathbf{a}$ is parallel to the normal, that is, perpendicular to the plane, which is the opposite situation. Three mutually orthogonal vectors satisfy the pairwise dot product condition and span all of space, so that option describes the least coplanar configuration possible, and a triple product of absolute value $1$ means a volume of one unit, not zero. The trap is swapping the scalar triple product for the vector triple product, two tests with nearly identical notation and opposite geometric meaning.",
      "difficulty": "stretch",
      "source": "in the style of Weatherburn, Elementary Vector Analysis"
    }
  ]
}
